Quadratic Functions


We are familiar with the notion of a linear function. This is a function which has the form \(y = mx + c\), where \(m\) corresponds to the gradient and \(c\) is the \(y\)-intercept. Graphs of these equation correspond to straight lines.

In contrast, a quadratic function is an equation of the form \(y = ax^2 + bx + c\), where \(a \not= 0\). This allows us to plot a quadratic in the Cartesian plane i.e. it allows us to plot quadratics on an \(x-y\) axis. Note that sometimes the notation \(f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c\) is used to show explicitly that it is a function of \(x\), we will discuss this in more detail in a later week. The squared term of the quadratic ensures that the resulting graph is no longer a straight line but is a curve called a parabola. This is an extremely important type of curve as they appear a lot in everyday life, such as in the curve of suspension bridges or the curve water makes when flowing out of a fountain. We shall begin by introducing some terminology.


Â 

  • The point at which the graph 'turns' is called the vertex or the turning point.
  • The turning point is a minimum if the graph curves upwards (is concave upwards).
  • The turning point is a maximum if the graph curves downwards (is concave downwards).
  • The vertical line which goes through the vertex is called the axis of symmetry and every parabola is symmetrical about its axis of symmetry.
  • The value of \(y\) where the graph crosses the y-axis is called the \(y\)-intercept.
  • The values of \(x\) where the graph crosses the \(x\)-axis are called the \(x\)-intercepts and they correspond to the roots of \(y = ax^2 + bx + c = 0\).
